This data set contains the following columns:

  • latitude degrees latitude (north of the Equator).

  • longitude degrees longitude (west of Greenwich).

  • tot.catch size of scallop catch at location specified by “latitude” and “longitude”

  • log.1.p.tot.catch is the log scallop catch size resulted via the transformation
    \[ log.1.p.tot.catch = \log( 1.0 + tot.catch ) \]

Consider as quantity of interest the log scallop catch size (log.1.p.tot.catch) whose spatial dependence we wish to investigate.

Consider the geostatistical model where the log scallop catch size is modeled an intrinsic random field \(\left(Z\left(s\right);s\in\mathcal{S}\right)\) with

\[\begin{equation} Z\left(s\right)=\mu\left(s\right)+\delta\left(s\right)\label{eq:-39} \end{equation}\]

where \(\mu\left(s\right)=\beta_{0}\) is an unknown constant drift, \(\delta\left(s\right)\) is an intrinsic random field, and \(s=(s_1,s_2)\) denotes the spatial coordinates longitude and latitude.

Copy and paste the code you wrote to produce the plot above.

rm(list=ls())
# load data
scallop.mod <- read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/georgios-stats/Spatio-Temporal_Statistics_Michaelmas_2024/refs/heads/main/Misc/scallop.mod.csv',sep=',')
scallop.mod.df <- as.data.frame(scallop.mod)
library(sp)
library(sf)
## Linking to GEOS 3.12.2, GDAL 3.8.5, PROJ 9.3.1; sf_use_s2() is TRUE
scallop.mod.map <- st_as_sf(scallop.mod.df, 
                         coords = c("longitude", "latitude"),
                         crs = 4326
                        )
scallop.mod.map$longitude <-  scallop.mod.df$longitude
scallop.mod.map$latitude <-  scallop.mod.df$latitude
# Compute the sample variogram cloud
library(gstat)
frml <- log.1.p.tot.catch ~ 1 
scallop.mod.map.cld <- variogram(object = frml,
                                 data = scallop.mod.map,
                                 cloud = TRUE
                                 )
# plot it
plot(scallop.mod.map.cld,
      xlab = 'distance', 
      ylab = 'gamma', 
      main = 'semivariogram cloud'
)

png('./non-par-semivar.png')
plot(scallop.mod.map.cld,
      xlab = 'distance', 
      ylab = 'gamma', 
      main = 'semivariogram cloud'
)
dev.off()

##   2

Consider a parametric semivariogram with mathematical formula

rm(list=ls())
# 0 load data
scallop.mod <- read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/georgios-stats/Spatio-Temporal_Statistics_Michaelmas_2024/refs/heads/main/Misc/scallop.mod.csv',sep=',')
scallop.mod.df <- as.data.frame(scallop.mod)
library(sp)
library(sf)
scallop.mod.map <- st_as_sf(scallop.mod.df, 
                         coords = c("longitude", "latitude"),
                         crs = 4326
                        )
scallop.mod.map$longitude <-  scallop.mod.df$longitude
scallop.mod.map$latitude <-  scallop.mod.df$latitude
# 1 Specify the semi variogram model
library(gstat)
frml <- log.1.p.tot.catch ~ 1 
smpl.vgm <- variogram(object = frml,
                      data = scallop.mod.map
                      )
vgm.obj <- vgm(psill = 0.5,
                model = "Nug", 
                range = 0
                )
vgm.obj <- vgm(psill = 1,
                 model = "Sph",
                 range = 100,
                 add.to = vgm.obj
                )
# 2 Fit the semi variogram model against the sample variogram
est.vgm <- fit.variogram(object = smpl.vgm,
                         model = vgm.obj
                         )
# 3 Print the estimated values for the parameters of the semi variogram model   
print(est.vgm)
##   model     psill    range
## 1   Nug 0.8428347  0.00000
## 2   Sph 3.8066333 37.49615
# 4 plot it 
plot(est.vgm, 
     cutoff = 50)

png("./fitted-semivariogram-scallop.mod.png")
plot(est.vgm, 
     cutoff = 50)
dev.off()

##   2

Consider the scallop data set .

Consider a parametric semivariogram with mathematical formula

\[ \gamma\left(h;\theta\right)=\gamma_{\text{nugget}}\left(h;\sigma_{\text{nugget}}^{2}\right)+\gamma_{\text{spherical}}\left(h;\sigma_{\text{spherical}}^{2},\phi_{\text{spherical}}\right) \] as defined above.

rm(list=ls())
# 0 load data
scallop.mod <- read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/georgios-stats/Spatio-Temporal_Statistics_Michaelmas_2024/refs/heads/main/Misc/scallop.mod.csv',sep=',')
scallop.mod.df <- as.data.frame(scallop.mod)
library(sp)
library(sf)
scallop.mod.map <- st_as_sf(scallop.mod.df, 
                         coords = c("longitude", "latitude"),
                         crs = 4326
                        )
scallop.mod.map$longitude <-  scallop.mod.df$longitude
scallop.mod.map$latitude <-  scallop.mod.df$latitude
# 1 Specify the semi variogram model
frml <- log.1.p.tot.catch ~ 1 
smpl.vgm <- variogram(object = frml,
                      data = scallop.mod.map
                      )
vgm.obj <- vgm(psill = 0.5,
                model = "Nug", 
                range = 0
                )
vgm.obj <- vgm(psill = 1,
                 model = "Sph",
                 range = 100,
                 add.to = vgm.obj
                )
# 2 Fit the semi variogram model against the sample variogram
est.vgm <- fit.variogram(object = smpl.vgm,
                         model = vgm.obj
                         )
# 3 Train the model
krige.fit <- gstat( formula = frml,
                    data = scallop.mod.map, 
                    model = est.vgm
                )
# 4. predict  

scallop.mod.new.df <- data.frame(longitude = c(-73.7), 
                              latitude = c(38.6) 
                              )
scallop.mod.new.sf <- st_as_sf(scallop.mod.new.df, 
                                coords = c("longitude", "latitude"),
                                crs = 4326
                                )
krige.prd <- predict(object = krige.fit,
                     newdata = scallop.mod.new.sf
                     )
## [using ordinary kriging]
krige.prd
